# Diabetes Prediction — Logistic Regression (Pima Indians Dataset)

An end-to-end machine learning pipeline that predicts whether a patient has diabetes based on diagnostic health measurements, using Logistic Regression with hyperparameter tuning.

## Project Structure

```
diabetes-prediction/
├── diabetes_prediction.py       # Full pipeline script
├── run_metrics.json             # Latest run's metrics (auto-generated)
├── model/
│   ├── diabetes_logreg_model.pkl
│   └── diabetes_scaler.pkl
└── figures/
    ├── eda_class_distribution.png
    ├── eda_correlation_heatmap.png
    ├── eda_feature_distributions.png
    ├── eval_confusion_matrix.png
    ├── eval_roc_curve.png
    ├── eval_precision_recall_curve.png
    └── feature_importance.png
```

## Dataset

The [Pima Indians Diabetes Dataset](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jbrownlee/Datasets/master/pima-indians-diabetes.data.csv), containing 768 patient records across 8 diagnostic features (Pregnancies, Glucose, Blood Pressure, Skin Thickness, Insulin, BMI, Diabetes Pedigree Function, Age) and a binary Outcome label (0 = no diabetes, 1 = diabetes).

Several columns (`Glucose`, `BloodPressure`, `SkinThickness`, `Insulin`, `BMI`) contain biologically impossible zero values, which are treated as hidden missing data and imputed using the class-wise median.

## Pipeline

1. **Load data** from the source CSV
2. **EDA** — class balance, correlations, feature distributions
3. **Clean & preprocess** — impute hidden missing values (zeros)
4. **Split & scale** — stratified 80/20 train/test split, `StandardScaler`
5. **Train** — Logistic Regression tuned via `GridSearchCV` (5-fold stratified CV, scored on ROC-AUC)
6. **Evaluate** — accuracy, confusion matrix, classification report, ROC-AUC
7. **Feature importance** — model coefficients
8. **Save artifacts** — model + scaler to `model/`
9. **Sample prediction** — demonstrates inference on a new patient

## Results

**Best hyperparameters:** `C=0.1`, `penalty='l2'`, `solver='lbfgs'`
**Best CV ROC-AUC:** 0.873

| Metric | Score |
|---|---|
| Test Accuracy | **70.78%** |
| Test ROC-AUC | **0.827** |

**Classification Report**

```
              precision    recall  f1-score   support

           0       0.77      0.79      0.78       100
           1       0.59      0.56      0.57        54

    accuracy                           0.71       154
   macro avg       0.68      0.67      0.67       154
weighted avg       0.70      0.71      0.71       154
```

Class `0` = No Diabetes, Class `1` = Diabetes. The model is noticeably weaker on the minority (diabetic) class — recall of 0.56 means it misses roughly 44% of actual diabetic cases in the test set. This is expected given the class imbalance (~65/35 split) and is worth addressing (see Next Steps).

